This paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category as it focuses on the effects of different information presentations on human decision-making. The use of Natural Language Generation (NLG) also suggests that it could belong to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The study's focus on measuring the effects of different presentations on decision-making also suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the study's use of uncertain data and its potential applications in various fields, such as healthcare and finance, suggest that it could belong to the Cybernetics (cs.CY) sub-category.
